											<td width="100%" valign="top">					
												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>FACTION, FACTION, EVERYWHERE....</font> - <small>Iztariani, Innoruuk</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>I've been working to up my faction in a number of
different cities, and many of them have one
variation or another on the bone chips quest,
which makes it overall one of the most useful
quests in the game.  Whenever I'm in an area with
lots of skels, I practise up on my "Sense Undead" 
and "Ward Undead" spells and hunt skels for a while.
The Everfrost Peaks and the Steamfont Mountains in
particular always seem to be densely populated by
the skeletal undead.<P>
I always keep a few stacks of chips in the bank,
and whenever I'm somewhere that I can raise faction
by using them, I expend a stack or two.  In my home
town of Erudin the shopkeeps in my guild (two of 
whom appear to be attached to the guild faction
rather then the impossible-to-raise Merchants of
Erudin faction) regard me warmly and give me
excellant pricing, and I'm already seeing similar
results in Kaladim, where they started off at
dubious.  Again, there seems to be the odd
shopkeeper (Tumpy Irontoe, in this case) who is in
a different faction then the other merchants and
cons substantially friendlier to me then they do
since I've done the bone chips a few dozen times.<P>
A lot of people can't be bothered doing even these
real simple quests, but I'd say they're definately
worth it, especially when your character is lower
level; the reward, between direct coinage and
salable items, can run as high as several gold per
attempt, and the increased faction makes it a lot
cheaper to buy and more beneficial to sell there.
It can also be a real big help if there's a quest
you either can't get until you have better faction
with that group, or that might give you
the wrong faction hit altogether. For example, the
Deepwater Harpoon quest out of Erudin has you kill
three different people, including a dwarf and a
gnome; if you haven't already built up the factions
with the groups that'll be harmed by these kills,
you could well find yourself KoS to these 
groups...and life is a lot easier if you're not
 being jumped by hostile NPCs all the time.
<P>
In addition to the Bone Chips, it's useful to keep
bat wings on hand, as many magic-user type guilds
have a quest involving these (sometimes involving
other bits and pieces as well, but these are usually
available in the nearest newbie zone).  The bat
wings are also a nicely salable item if you're
passing through somewhere with a levitation-required
zone, for example they're usually snapped up fast
at 2p to 3p per stack in High Hold by people doing
the warrior room.  And necromancers and
shadowknights both apparently need these to summon
pets with, and will also pay a nice price per stack for them rather then gathering them themselves.
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
